{t|dv|ކެބެޖް}}\n* Friulian: {{t|fur|cauli}}, {{t|fur|brocul}}, {{t|fur|verge|f}}, {{t|fur|verze|f}}\n* Georgian: {{t|ka|ხვიტი}}, {{t|ka|კეჟერა}}\n*: Old Georgian: {{t|oge|კალნაბი}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|כְּרוּב|m|tr=kruv}}\n* Hindi: {{t+|hi|गोभी|f}}, {{t+|hi|कोबी|f}} {{qualifier|obsolete}}, {{t+|hi|करमकल्ला|m}}\n* Ido: {{t+|io|kaulo}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|kol}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|cabáiste|m}}, {{t|ga|cál|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|甘藍|tr=かんらん, kanran}}, {{t+|ja|玉菜|tr=たまな, tamana}}\n* Kannada: {{t+|kn|ಎಲೆಕೋಸು}}\n* Kazakh: {{t|kk|қырыққабат}}, {{t|kk|орамжапырақ}}, {{t|kk|капуста}}\n* Khmer: {{t|km|ស្ពៃក្ដោប}}, {{t+|km|ស្ពៃ}}\n* Kurdish:\n*: Central Kurdish: {{t|ckb|کەلەرم}}\n*: Northern Kurdish: {{t|kmr|kebic}}, {{t+|kmr|kelem}}\n* Kyrgyz: {{t+|ky|керем}}\n* Lao: {{t|lo|ກາດຫໍ່}}, {{t|lo|ກະລຳປີ}}\n* Lezgi: {{t|lez|келем}}\n* Lü: {{t|khb|ᦕᧅᦂᦱᧆᦠᦸᧈ}}\n* Luganda: {{t|lg|emboga}}\n* Macedonian: {{t|mk|зелка|f}}\n* Malagasy: {{t+|mg|salady}}\n* Malay:\n*: Brunei Malay: {{t|kxd|kubis}}\n* Malayalam: {{t+|ml|കാബേജ്}}, {{t+|ml|മുട്ടക്കോസ്}}\n* Manipuri: {{t+|mni|ꯀꯣꯕꯤ}}\n* Māori: {{t+|mi|puka}}, {{t|mi|kāpiti}}, {{t|mi|nīko}}\n* Marathi: {{t|mr|कोबी|m}}\n* Miyako: {{t|mvi|玉菜|tr=たまなー, tamanā}}\n* Mongolian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t+|mn|байцаа}}\n*: Mongolian script: {{t|mn|ᠪᠠᠢᠴᠠᠢ}}, {{t|mn|ᠪᠥᠭᠡᠷᠡᠩᠬᠡᠢ ᠴᠠᠭᠠᠨ ᠨᠣᠭᠣᠭ᠎ᠠ}}\n* Navajo: {{t|nv|chʼil łigaii}}, {{t|nv|atʼééké bijish}}\n* Nepali: {{t+|ne|गोभी}}, {{t|ne|बन्दगोभी}}\n* Norman: {{t|nrf|caboche|f}}\n* Occitan: {{t+|oc|caulet|m}}, {{t+|oc|caul|m}}, {{t+|oc|chaul|m}}\n* Okinawan: {{t|ryu|玉菜|tr=たまなー, tamanā}}\n* Old English: {{t|ang|cāwel|m}}\n* Oromo: {{t|om|raafuu}}\n* Persian:\n*: Dari: {{t|prs|کَلَم}}\n*: Iranian Persian: {{t|fa-ira|کَلَم}}\n* Punjabi:\n*: Gurmukhi: {{t|pa|ਬੰਦ ਗੋਭੀ|f}}, {{t+|pa|ਗੋਭੀ|f}}\n* Romansh: {{t|rm|giabus|m}}, {{t|rm|gibus|m}}, {{t|rm|gibo|m}}, {{t|rm|baguos|m}}, {{t|rm|tiasta|f}}, {{t|rm|cavazza|f}}\n* Rwanda-Rundi: {{t|rw|ishu}}\n* Sardinian: {{t|sc|càule|m}}\n* Scots: {{t|sco|cabbitch}}, {{t|sco|kail}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t|sh|ку̀пус|m}}, {{t|sh|зе̑ље|n}}\n*: Latin: {{t+|sh|kùpus|m}}, {{t+|sh|zȇlje|n}}\n* Sicilian: {{t+|scn|cavulu}}, {{t+|scn|càvulu}}, {{t+|scn|caulu}}, {{t+|scn|càulu}}\n* Sinhalese: {{t+|si|ගෝවා}}\n* Slovene: {{t+|sl|zelje|n}}\n* Somali: {{t|so|sallar}}\n* Sotho: {{t+|st|khabetjhe}}\n* Swahili: {{t+|sw|kabeji|c9|c10}}, {{t+|sw|kabichi|c9|c10}}\n* Tajik: {{t+|tg|карам}}\n* Taos: {{t|twf|kùliʼína}}\n* Tigrinya: {{t|ti|ካውሎ}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|dürme}}, {{t+|tr|kelem}}, {{t+|tr|lahana}},\n* Turkmen: {{t|tk|kellem}}, {{t|tk|kelem}}\n* Urdu: {{t|ur|گوبھی|f}}\n* Uyghur: {{t|ug|كاپۇستا}}\n* Uzbek: {{t+|uz|karam}}, {{t|uz|kapusta}}\n* Venetan: {{t|vec|càvol}}, {{t|vec|càorlo}}, {{t|vec|càoło}}\n* Volapük: {{t+|vo|brasid}}\n* Yoron: {{t|yox|甘藍|tr=かんだん, kandan}}\n* Zhuang: {{t|za|byaekgienjsim}}, {{t|za|byaeklup}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To form a head like that of the cabbage.\n#: {{co|en|to make lettuce '''cabbage'''}}\n# {{lb|en|intransitive|slang}} To do nothing; to [[idle]]; [[veg out]].\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=2006|author=Steve Mckevitt|title=Why the World Is Full of Useless Things|page=38|passage=How effective the project was is a moot point, because there were never any studies carried out to see whether children benefited from '''cabbaging''' in front of the TV rather than interacting with a teacher.}}\n# {{lb|en|slang|AAVE}} To be [[kill]]ed or [[murder]]ed, such as by being shot in the head.\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|en|brassica}}\n* {{l|en|broccoflower}}\n* {{l|en|broccoli}}\n* {{l|en|broccolini}}\n* {{l|en|Brussels sprouts}}\n* {{l|en|cabbage tree}}\n* {{l|en|carbage}}\n* {{l|en|cauliflower}}\n* {{l|en|Chinese cabbage}}\n* {{l|en|Chinese broccoli}}, {{l|en|Chinese kale}}\n* {{l|en|collard greens}}\n* {{l|en|kale}}\n* {{l|en|kohlrabi}}\n* {{l|en|sauerkraut}}\n* {{l|en|red cabbage}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nUnclear. Perhaps from {{bor|en|nl||*kabbassen}}, from {{cog|fro|cabasser||put into a basket}}, from {{m|fro|cabas}}.<ref>{{R:Century 1911}}</ref> Alternatively, perhaps from an earlier word {{m|en||*carbage|t=shred}}, a potential variant of {{m|en||*garbage|t=wheat straw}}.<ref name=\"Dict\"/>\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|-}}\n\n# {{lb|en|slang}} Scraps of cloth which are left after a garment has been cut out, which tailors traditionally kept.\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[embezzle]] or [[purloin]]; to [[pilfer]], to [[steal#Verb|steal]].\n#* {{RQ:Arbuthnot Law|year=1733|chapter=X|chaptername=Of John Bull's Second Wife, and the Good Advice that She Gave Him|page=30|passage=[Y]our Butler purloins your Liquor, and your Brevver ſells your Hogvvaſh; {{...}} your Taylor, inſtead of Shreds, '''cabages''' vvhole Yards of Cloth; {{...}}}}\n#* {{RQ:Lincoln Pratt's Patients|chapter=VIII|passage=We toted in the wood and got the fire going nice and comfortable. Lord James still set in one of the chairs and Applegate had '''cabbaged''' the other and was hugging the stove.}}\n\n===References===\n<references/>\n\n{{C|en|Brassicas|Palm trees}}"}}